Mini project 2: primary productivity in coastal waters

In this project you're again given a dataset and some questions. The data for this project come from the EPA's National Aquatic Resource Surveys, and in particular the National Coastal Condition Assessment (NCCA); broadly, you'll do an exploratory analysis of primary productivity in coastal waters.

By way of background, chlorophyll A is often used as a proxy for primary productivity in marine ecosystems; primary producers are important because they are at the base of the food web. Nitrogen and phosphorus are key nutrients that stimulate primary production.

In the data folder you'll find water chemistry data, site information, and metadata files. It might be helpful to keep the metadata files open when tidying up the data for analysis. It might also be helpful to keep in mind that these datasets contain a considerable amount of information, not all of which is relevant to answering the questions of interest. Notice that the questions pertain somewhat narrowly to just a few variables. It's recommended that you determine which variables might be useful and drop the rest.

As in the first mini project, there are accurate answers to each question that are mutually consistent with the data, but there aren't uniquely correct answers. You will likely notice that you have even more latitude in this project than in the first, as the questions are slightly broader. Since we've been emphasizing visual and exploratory techniques in class, you are encouraged (but not required) to support your answers with graphics.

The broader goal of these mini projects is to cultivate your problem-solving ability in an unstructured setting. Your work will be evaluated based on the following:

  • choice of method(s) used to answer questions;
  • clarity of presentation;
  • code style and documentation.

Please write up your results separately from your codes; codes should be included at the end of the notebook.

Part 2: exploratory analysis

Answer each question below and provide a visualization supporting your answer. A description and interpretation of the visualization should be offered.

Comment: you can either designate your plots in the codes section with clear names and reference them in your answers; or you can export your plots as image files and display them in markdown cells.

What is the apparent relationship between nutrient availability and productivity?

Comment: it's fine to examine each nutrient -- nitrogen and phosphorus -- separately, but do consider whether they might be related to each other.

*We examined Total Phosphorus and Total Nitrogen against Chlorophyll A. From these two graphs we can see that as nutrients increases, ptoductivity increases with it. Both graphs have a positive correlation with very few outliars. In many coastal regions in the given data, Total Phosphorus and Total Nitrogen are nurtients found in the same body of water. From this we can conclude that the presence of both nitrogen and phosphorus increases the presence of Chlorophyll A.

The reasons for this is because with the increase of Nitrogen and Phosphorus it causes certain components in the water like algae to bloom, thus producing more Chlorophyll A.*

Are there any notable differences in available nutrients among U.S. coastal regions?

*From the graphs we can see that in the East Coast, Great Lakes and West Coast as Nitrogen increases Chlorophyll A increases. Nitrogen seems to be more apparent within the Great Lakes and the East Coast. It is easier to see outliers within this data and we can see that there are very high levels of Nitrogen and Chlorophyll A in the Great Lakes in some cases. Additionally, we can see that in the Gulf Coast, once Total Nitrogen reaches about 1.0, Chlorophyll A Productvity and Nitrogen Nutrients will drop drastically and will not go back up at all.

In the second graph we can clearly see that there is far less amounts of Total Phosphorus compared to Total Nitrogen. For Total Phosphorus and Chlorophyll A we can see that Phosphorus and Chlorophyll A is more apparent in the East Coast and the Great Lakes compared to the Gulf Coast and West Cost. There are not as many apparent outliers within this data in constrast to the Total Nitrogen vs. Chlorophyll A data. Also, we can see that when Phosphorus is at about .18 phosphorus will drop thus, Chlorophyll A drops but then Phosphorus increases again at .23 and so does Chlorophyll A Productivity.

From this data we can conclude that there is a direct relationship between Productivity and Nutrients and when either Total Nitrogen or Total Phosphorus increase or decrease, Chlorophyll A will increase or decrease with them.*

Based on the 2010 data, does productivity seem to vary geographically in some way?

If so, explain how; If not, explain what options you considered and ruled out.

*Using longitude and latitude to see geogrpahically we can see that productivity varies from location to location. For example, some parts of Lake Erie productivity (Chlorophyll A) is at 144.63 but in some other parts of Lake Erie it is at 31.79. Thus showing that productivity is vastly different even in specific parts of one region. By using the interactive map we can see that productivity is least within the Gulf Coast and greatest within the Great Lakes.

Additionally I created a histogram using the variable NCCR_REG which is all the regions within the given data. From this histogram we can see that productivity is greatest within the Great Lakes and the North East. Thus we can conclude that since Chlorophyll levels are highest in these regions, nurtients are also greatest in these regions due to the direct relationship of the two.*

How does primary productivity in California coastal waters change seasonally in 2010, if at all?

Does your result make intuitive sense?

*From the graphs we can that productivity is very high within the summer months. For Nitrogen, the months June and July have the highest amounts of productivty. This is due to the increase in Nitrogen and Phosphorus within the water during the hotter months since materials in the atmosphere like Nitrogen and Phosphorus sink lower during the warmer months, thus causing Chlorophyll A to increase. Additionally we can see that phosphorus is strictly increasing within July but is fluctuating within the other summer months with respect to Chlorophyll A. Since there are less data points for phosphorus it is more clear to see the data changing over the course of the months.

In Autumn we can see that productivity increases drastically since Nitrogen increases drastically within the Autumn seasons. There is much more Nitrogen present in comparison to Phosphorus. There is still an increase within the Autumn seasons with Phosphorus as well but there is not much of a drastic increase. There is much more nitrogen and Phosphorus present within September compared to October, thus we can conclude as the weather gets colder there is less nutrtients present in the water.

Overall, from our data we can conclude that as the weather gets colder there is less nutrients within the water so productivity decreases within the colder months.*

Does the depth of the water in coastal waters change productivity monthly in 2010?

*As we can see from the data, each months follows a very similar distirbution. When the depth of the water is anywhere from 0-40, the productivity of Chlorophyll A is anywhere from 0-40. We can see that productvity is most consisntent within August and July and that there is a steady, slow productivity increase. In every month productivity seems to spike when the water depth is around 10. We can also see that over productivty is the lowest for the months May and June even where the water depth is around 10.

This follows our earlier observations that productivity is the highest of all within the month of July.*

Nitro_Graph = alt.Chart(ncca_new_raw).mark_circle(opacity=0.5).encode(
    x = alt.X('Total Nitrogen', scale = alt.Scale(type = 'log')),
    y = alt.Y('Chlorophyll A', title = 'Chlorophyll A', scale = alt.Scale(type = 'sqrt'))) # scale properly so data is proper for analyzing
Phos_Graph = alt.Chart(ncca_new_raw).mark_circle(opacity=0.5).encode(
    x = alt.X('Total Phosphorus', scale = alt.Scale(type = 'sqrt')),
    y = alt.Y('Chlorophyll A', title = 'Chlorophyll A', scale = alt.Scale(type = 'sqrt'))) # scale properly so data is proper for analyzing

display(Nitro_Graph)
display(Phos_Graph)

scatter = alt.Chart(ncca_new_raw_1).mark_circle(opacity=0.75).encode(
    x = alt.X('Total Nitrogen', scale = alt.Scale(type = 'sqrt')),
    y = alt.Y('Chlorophyll A', title = 'Chlorophyll A', scale = alt.Scale(type = 'sqrt')),
             color = 'NCA_REGION')

smooth = scatter.transform_loess(
    groupby = ['NCA_REGION'],
    on = 'Total Nitrogen', # x variable
    loess = 'Chlorophyll A', # y variable
    bandwidth = 0.25 # how smooth?
).mark_line(color = 'black')
